text: Hello Alex,  I hope you are doing well. Let me start by saying first "jalape√±os." I know this is one of your older videos, but it is so impactful. Thank you for taking the time to share your story with us.   I have always loved analyzing data. I retired from the Marine Corps a few years back and have been trying to find my place in a new career. I naturally look toward operations management; it is my comfort zone. I held a position as a Business Analyst as my first role right out of the service and loved the work, but I felt something was missing. I always used data to help me make decisions, but I didn't have the necessary KSAs to take me to the next level, so I went back into operations management.   Based on your recommendations in some other videos, I started taking classes on Coursera. While I have not made it to where I want to be yet, I know I will make it there.  I will touch bases with you in the future with an update once I make it; but, I will say this up front:  Thank you for being a part of my success.   -Andre

author: @noor_51
text: Yes, career change to Data Analytics is very possible and the best thing to have happened to me. Just ensure that you get some credible certifications to prove your competence. This will make it very easy to get recognized among the crowd. There are tons of them, some are even free like the Alteryx certification. I can help guide anyone to pass the Alteryx exams. I am already certified.   Before all these, I graduated with my first degree in Mathematics. However, it was very tough finding a job with that degree. I then started learning Data Analytics on YouTube and acquired intermediate competence in using various software like Excel, SQL, Tableau, and Power BI. Despite having these skills, it was still very challenging to land my first job because I didn't have the credentials to justify my skills. So I resorted to online freelancing while building my professional network. It was then that an idea struck me to seek certification that could enable me prove my competence in the said areas. However, another major obstacle was that majority of the certifications like Tableau, Power Bi, and Oracle were a bit expensive for me since I didn't have a job yet. So I learnt of Alteryx free certification and aced it https://www.dropbox.com/s/9imtpea345s166h/Alteryx%20Cert.jpg?dl=0. It became a good starting point for me and later on I was able to raise funds and register for the paid certifications. I am glad and appreciative for the progress I have made ever since.

author: @brandijean5186
text: Hi Alex! Your story is so inspiring to me, as our journey has a lot of similarities. I graduated with an associates degree as a physical therapist assistant, but by the time I graduated I was so burnt out and unenthused with patient care that I knew I couldn't work in the field. Shortly after graduating, and somewhat randomly, I landed a job as a data collection specialist for a local hospital. Right now, I'm looking for a data analyst role and it would be SO COOL if it was with a healthcare analytics company! I truly hope I am following in your footsteps, haha. I have actually just completed my first semester of a computer science bachelor's degree because I really love the subject. While I don't know if I want to be a data analyst forever, I know I want to be one right now - but the journey is incredibly daunting. I appreciate you sharing your story, as I am at my complete wits end trying to find a job. I don't feel like I know enough to get my first job, and the job market seems increasingly competitive.   This gave me some inspiration and hope that someone who doesn't really know a lot about being a data analyst in the grand scheme of things (aka, Me) CAN land an entry level role and go on to be successful. Thank you so much for sharing, and I can't wait to watch more of your videos.  - Brandi

author: @pabloruiz5407
text: Jalape√±os! This video is really inspiring. By just listening one can tell that you are being super honest and open about it! Many of the thoughts you share are the same ones I've had/I'm having, since I'm personally kind of in the mid-point of your data analyst story :)  I feel like lots of people had had the same challenges: trying to earn the first or second job knowing almost nothing of the field, or knowing just super-specific stuff but not really how to apply it or how it fits in a data analytics team. But for people out there: don't let this give you impostor syndrome! The truth is most of the data analysts I know now really did not have any formal education on the field before starting their first position (many had maybe just a degree in engineering or business administration, but no coding or data analytics knowledge). These positions are so demanded that I feel like most of them are covered by people that have been self-taught and come from other areas of expertise.  About your specific story Alex, it sounds like you spent so much extra time at every job. It is motivating and inspiring, but for other people I just wanted to say that it is perfectly fine to do your normal amount of work and normal hours, and progression will come anyways if you are professional and work relatively well (and some luck is always great to have). In any normal company, part of your work time should be spent actually learning things from your daily work, so that you can be more productive for your team. I guess I would just like to tell people to take care when putting that extra effort, watch out for burnout, which is very tipical in the field. On my experience, it's better to take things slow but steady!

text: Hi Alex. First, how are you and your family? I hope all are doing well! Secondly, I watched the video in its entirety and interestingly enough, though I do not currently aspire to become a data analyst. I found your video to be extremely informative and inspirational on career change and how you navigated pivoting. Through your determination and dedication, you conveyed how it can be done, but what really translated to me most, was the underlying message of limitless possibilities for achieving that which we truly aspire. One thought went through my mind is how you mentioned early on, how you enjoy working with people. I wonder how much you actually get to work with people ‚Äì perhaps in developing improvement processes and analyses for various departments? I also enjoy developing ways for making processes simpler and more efficient, particularly when others haven‚Äôt any idea how and in showing or helping them, this at times can make have such a profound impact.   I do have a pretty simple question for you though (and it isn't about why my script isn‚Äôt working üòâ). My question pertains to working with recruiters directly. You had mentioned those you used initially reached out to you, but can you recommend ways or even companies for initiating these connections in effort to get the job searching started? I too, am transitioning my career and have already began making many changes for launching this transition but was curious what your thoughts were based on your knowledge and past experiences.

author: @nyansaphoenix4970
text: I am so grateful and thankful that you were born and pushed through to get the knowledge you are sharing us. I am a mother of 6 grandmother of 8. I wanted to be a Pathologist but my young and dumbselfmade a decision that caused me to have major legal problems  for 10 years of my young life. Since this happened I was lost and felt like that door was closed.  So I just did any and everything. I knew I wanted a great respectful and challenging career but had no idea how to get it. Long story short....I sold cars for 20 years but I have acquired a deep seeded hate for this field. There was just too many bosses not enough Indians in an extremely toxic environment. At the suggestion of a friend that is a software engineer he introduced me to data analytics. I was so in love with this career field......until.. I did extensive research took an Big Data online class....the first class I was lost. I played with SQL but didn't realize we would be going full speed in this class. I crammed and crammed everything I could but decided...I don't want to memorize I really want to know this stuff. So I tried to take a less advanced class and get my money back but they weren't trying to hear it.....then covid happened. I got custody of my 3 grandchildren. We all got covid. I gave up and went to the worst job I ever had in my life back to selling cars thinking things may be better someplace else.....boy was I wrong. Anyway my Long story short...with all my health issues, family issues, ect...I made a 100% decision to become an Analyst at whatever the cost. I am 48 years old and I figured 3 years dedication to learning and putting everything I have to better the rest of my life. I can be an inspiration to myself, my children, grandchildren, and for those changing a career later in life. I  will have a good 7 years to work I'm the field if I live that long but if I do I will be able to plant so many seeds within my family. I want to thank you for sharing you experiences and saying that if you made it to the end of the video you will be a successful analyst. I felt those words so deep in my soul I had to pull over and type the JALAPE√ëOS. üòä

author: @brianjacobs8839
text: I was watching this video after midnight after signing up for a Data Analyst course and completing week one. Truth be told I was going to split the 40 mins in two parts üòÜ because I was so damn sleepy. I made it to the end so Jalape√±o! I worked for a big international oil company for ten years and worked with data during migration projects, but never on a real analytical level. Most of the experts told me that you can break into the field without a degree. Sure employers do like degrees but even someone like with me with a high school diploma only, worked on data migration projects with SAP and IBM consultants. Always felt like a imposter though but my contributions were significant on country wide levels. I never bothered to get 'certified' and acquire skills like SQL etc which I regret now. Skills that I decided to start aquiring now. Interestingly enough I told my girlfriend I need additional skills to secure our future financially. That stood out in your video. Providing for others is a great motivator. Great channel mate. Wishing you and the family much success and happiness.

text: Jalape√±os üòä. Wow. Thank you for sharing your story. And though this is your journey it is one that is shared by many. You‚Äôre correct in saying it‚Äôs not just luck, it takes hard work too. My wife feels that when people say she‚Äôs lucky for having the job that she has, it takes away from the hard work she‚Äôs put into it.  You really motivated me to start making a change to invest in myself. I‚Äôve had roles where I felt I was the weakest link because I didn‚Äôt have the technical knowledge to perform the job, but because I knew how to ask the right questions and had great people skills my managers really liked me and wished that I had stayed. I have three kids (3, 6, 10) and due to COVID they‚Äôre doing homeschooling but I need to make time to develop my skills so when I‚Äôm ready to go back to work I am competitive. My people skills and experience can only take me so far so I really need to build my technical skills. I do have a mechanical engineering degree, but that didn‚Äôt prepare me for a career as a data analyst and from people I‚Äôve spoken to, there isn‚Äôt one degree, at least not until recently, that teaches you sql, python, etc. These are things you need to learn on your own or on the job. author: @jwatsondp1
text: Jalapenos I started out as an Engineer Trainee writing FORTRAN programs. Then I became a technician developing DBase databases. Then I became an administrative assistant using a Wang word processor and Lotus 123 spreadsheets. Then I became a computer instructor teaching students how to use Apple IIe computer software (games, word processing, spreadsheets, databases, etc.). Then I became an IT Support/Business Analyst creating advanced Excel spreadsheet data analysis solutions for engineers, managers and accountants. Then I became an Access database developer. Then I became a SQL Server/Oracle database developer and SPSS programmer. I have also picked up Tableau, Power BI, SharePoint, R/Python and Regression Analysis skills.

text: Hi Alex! Thank you for your videos.  I have been a chef for almost 13 years and decided to leave the industry and decided to switch career. When I moved into a senior position and had to start doing paperwork like costings, purchasings and inventory, I had to work with Excel and that was when I found out I had a liking for calculations driven by logic.   I was always curious to find out more about Excel functions(and later on pivot tables and power query) and analysing my sales & purchases with them. E.g "if I increased the selling price of a dish, how much more would i be able to make based on the average quantity sold?" Or "How much money can I saved if I switched to another supplier for ingredient x or y based on my average usage?" .. stuff like that.   I only have a diploma in culinary arts and no computer science background. I couldn't get into a university because our family just couldn't afford it, so I went to work   What I like to ask is   1. What age were you when u got you real first job as a data analyst?  2. Would a data analyst job be suitable for me?  3. Arent you afraid that by sharing your codes/scripts(the one that automated a whole day's work into 5mins) people might take it, claim credit for themselves and get rid of you?   Like as a chef, we never give the full recipe, for the fear that evil bosses will take it, get rid of us and higher someone cheaper to do my job.  Sorry for the long comment, your video is very real and i can connect to what you said about having no background but trying something new. You're a good man to share your knowledge and experience! author: @badeemabidurken4420
text: Heya.  Thanks for your videos. You're inspiring to listen to. I fully think data analyst is my calling. Born to do it. It feels like about the only thing I could be good at. I felt like dropping some unsolicited self description of why I think I suit the task and maybe someone will find some use in my comment. Or maybe I will just put into words and onto the internet, a feeling that I've found my passion.  I'm a serial dropout. I dropped out of BSc physics/math/python programming, BSc biochemistry, Cert computing, Cert IT. I passed diploma in business, Certificate in personal training. And there is a handful of other small courses and minor papers I picked up too with mixed success. Psychology, stats, geology, plumbing and some others. I was unstable in many ways and sticking to something has been a challenge, despite plenty of A's along the way which became F's when I stopped attending.  I truly love love abstract, theoretical, technical problem solving and especially analysis. I love getting to the bottom of a pool of data and deciding what it all means and how it can justify how best to approach a complex problem. I've been curious my whole life and taught myself all manor of things on the internet from political theories to particle physics, psychology and cosmology. I've carried this momentum by myself my whole life (I'm now 30) with no-one to share it with or discuss it with as no-one around me is curious minded. Discussions about any of this is always derailed or twisted into a dismissive joke.  I've had about 27 jobs in my life. All blue collar which was so droll. I spent a long time depressed as hell because I was looking at the stars while stacking boxes, warehousing, cleaning or doing factory work. I had to do it to pay bills and I never really had the time to slow down and work on something on the side. My parents always demanded a lot of my time to help them on the farm. They're far more simple, practical, concrete and shallow minded people. So any of my intrigue was always met with frustration and exasperation as it wasn't related to the menial task at hand. I'm even pretty accomplished in the alpaca shearing shed now. I'm possibly the second best alpaca shearers hand in New Zealand. I chose not to move up to alpaca shearer because the work is more challenging and physical than is imaginable without first person experience. 13 hour days 7 days a week for 100 days straight if you are keen and get into it. Average joe would be flat as a pancake by morning tea time with the physicality of this job.  I've just completed building myself a 3 screen PC perfect for a workstation and learning from. I can't wait to rip into all of this. I'm hungry for the knowledge and can't wait to enter this whole new exciting field of curiosity food. An IT friend of mine has recommended that I do my Comptia A+ certification and get into helpdesk for a good entry into the IT industry and then I can go from there to start learning data analysis. I hope this is a good direction, as I have just started in this direction.
